entational state transfer|REST]], [[AWS S3]]\n|-\n! {{rh}} |[https://www.quobyte.com/product Quobyte]\n| Java, C++\n| {{proprietary}}\n| [[Posix#POSIX.1|POSIX]], [[Filesystem in Userspace|FUSE]], [[Network File System|NFS]], [[SMB/CIFS]], [[HDFS]], [[AWS S3]], [[TensorFlow| TensorFlow Plugin]], [[Command-line interface|CLI]], Rest API\n|}\n\n==Remote access==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width: auto; table-layout: fixed;  text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"background: #ececec\"\n!| Name\n! Run by\n! Access API\n|-\n| {{rh}} |[[Amazon S3]]\n| [[Amazon.com]]\n| [[HTTP]] ([[REST]]/[[SOAP]])\n|-\n| {{rh}} |[[Google Cloud Storage]]\n| [[Google]]\n| [[HTTP]] ([[REST]])\n|-\n| {{rh}} |SWIFT (part of [[OpenStack]])\n| [[Rackspace]], [[Hewlett-Packard]], others\n| [[HTTP]] ([[REST]])\n|-\n| {{rh}} |[[Microsoft Azure]]\n| [[Microsoft]]\n| [[HTTP]] ([[REST]])\n|-\n| {{rh}} |IBM Cloud Object Storage\n|[[IBM]] (formerly [[Cleversafe]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www-03.ibm.com/press/us/en/pressrelease/47776.wss|title=IBM Plans to Acquire Cleversafe for Object Storage in Cloud|date=2015-10-05|website=www-03.ibm.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n| [[HTTP]] ([[REST]])\n|}\n\n==Comparison==\nSome researchers have made a functional and experimental analysis of several distributed file systems including HDFS, Ceph, Gluster, Lustre and old (1.6.x) version of MooseFS, although this document is over 4 years old and a lot of information may be outdated (e.g. MooseFS has at the time of writing this stable 2.0 and beta 3.0 version and HA for Metadata Server - since 2.0 and it is not mentioned in this document).<ref>{{cite web|last1=S\u00e9guin|first1=Cyril|last2=Depardon|first2=Benjamin|last3=Le Mahec|first3=Ga\u00ebl|title=Analysis of Six Distributed File Systems|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/file/index/docid/789086/filename/a_survey_of_dfs.pdf|website=HAL}}</ref>\n\nThe cloud based remote distributed storage from major vendors have different APIs and different consistency models.<ref>{{cite web|title=Data Consistency Models of Public Cloud Storage Services: Amazon S3, Google Cloud Storage and Windows Azure Storage|url=https://www.systutorials.com/3551/data-consistency-models-of-public-cloud-storage-services-amazon-s3-google-cloud-storage-and-windows-azure-storage/|website=SysTutorials|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n*[[Distributed file system]]\n*[[List of file systems#Distributed file systems|List of file systems, the ''Distributed file systems'' section]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Storage virtualization}}\n{{File systems}}\n\n[[Category:Network file systems]]\n[[Category:Software comparisons|Distributed file systems]]\n{{compu-storage-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProprietary:NFS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_distributed_file_systems"}
{"title_page": "Blair Witch (film)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|The Blair Witch Project}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name               = Blair Witch\n| image              = Blair Witch 2016 poster.png\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Theatrical release poster\n| director           = [[Adam Wingard]]\n| producer           = {{plainlist|\n* [[Roy Lee]]\n* Steven Schneider\n* [[Keith Calder]]\n* Jess Calder\n}}\n| writer             = [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]]\n| starring           = {{plainlist|\n* [[James Allen McCune]]\n* [[Callie Hernandez]]\n* Brandon Scott\n* Corbin Reid\n* [[Valorie Curry]]\n* Wes Robinson\n}}\n| music              = Adam Wingard\n| cinematography     = Robby Baumgartner\t\n| editing            = Louis Cioffi\n| studio = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n* [[Vertigo Entertainment]]\n* Room 101\n* Snoot Entertainment\n}}\n| distributor          = Lionsgate\n| released             = {{Film date|2016|7|22|[[San Diego Comic-Con]]|2016|9|16|United States}}\n| runtime              = 89 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 89:03 --><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/blair-witch-film|title=''BLAIR WITCH'' (15)|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=August 17, 2016|accessdate=August 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| country              = {{plainlist|* United States\n* Canada<ref name=\"LUMIERE\">{{cite web|url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=67903 |title=Film: Blair Witch |website=[[LUMIERE]]|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| language             = English\n| budget               = $5 million<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doty|first1=Meriah|title=Will \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Beat \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019s Baby\u2019 in Box Office Battle of Long-Delayed Sequels?|url=https://thewrap.com/blair-witch-bridget-jones-baby-box-office/|website=[[TheWrap]]|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=BOM/>\n| gross                = $45.2 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=woods2016.htm |title=Blair Witch (2016) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Blair Witch''''' is a 2016 American [[supernatural horror film]] directed by [[Adam Wingard]] and written by [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Nordine|url=https://indiewire.com/article/the-woods-trailer-adam-wingard-found-footage-horror-20160510|title=''The Woods'' Trailer: Adam Wingard Takes Us Camping in New Found-Footage Horror Flick|website=[[Indiewire]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref> It is the third film in the ''[[Blair Witch]]'' series and a direct sequel to the 1999 film ''[[The Blair Witch Project]]'', ignoring the events of its 2000 follow-up film ''[[Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2]]'', given the events of that film being a [[play within a play|film within a film]].{{efn|name=BookOfShadows|In the tie-in documentary to ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'', ''Shadow of the Blair Witch'', the events of ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'' are presented in-universe as a film adaptation based on the \"Black Hills murders\" that took place shortly after the events of ''The Blair Witch Project''. This documentary presents the events of ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'' as a film within a film. ''Shadow of the Blair Witch'' follows \"the real Jeff Patterson\u2019s defense team as the case prepares for trial and as the public reacts to plans to fictionalize the case\u2019s events for the big screen from the defense's point-of-view. Protests of the film ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'' are discussed within the documentary coming from both the families of those involved with the case and from the Wiccan community as a whole. Rachel Moskowitz and Andre Brooks respectively portray the \"real\" Kim Diamond and Jeffrey Patterson within the documentary.}} ''Blair Witch'' stars [[James Allen McCune]], [[Callie Hernandez]], Brandon Scott, Corbin Reid, [[Valorie Curry]], and Wes Robinson. The film, shot in a [[Found footage (film technique)|found footage]] style, follows a group of college students and their local guides who venture into the Black Hills Forest in Maryland to uncover the mysteries surrounding the prior disappearance of [[Heather Donahue]], the sister of one of the characters.\n\nDevelopment of the film began in September 2009, when creators of the franchise [[Daniel Myrick]] and [[Eduardo S\u00e1nchez (director)|Eduardo S\u00e1nchez]] announced their intent to produce a third ''Blair Witch'' film. The film was a sequel to the first film, would potentially contain the actors from the first film in some context, and would not reference any of the events from ''Book of Shadows''. In 2011, S\u00e1nchez remarked that further development on a sequel depended on getting [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] to approve the idea and for his and Myrick's schedule to match up.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The film went into [[development hell]], and later the script was trowed aside. In 2013, a third ''Blair Witch'' film was again in talks, with Wingard and Barrett being hired to work on a new script.\n\nInitially, the film's connection to the ''Blair Witch'' franchise was kept secret, with the film having been shot under the fake title, ''The Woods''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Roffman|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/07/adam-wingards-the-woods-is-actually-a-sequel-to-the-blair-witch-project/|title=Adam Wingard's ''The Woods'' is actually a sequel to ''The Blair Witch Project''|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|publisher=Consequence Holdings, LLC|location=Chicago, Illinois|date=July 23, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=July 25, 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, it was revealed at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] that the film marketed with the faux-title ''The Woods'' actually turned out to be the sequel ''Blair Witch''.\n\nThe film premiered at San Diego Comic-Con on July 22, 2016 and was screened at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 11, before being theatrically released in the United States on September 16, by Lionsgate.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michelle|last=Smith|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/3908212|title=''The Woods'' Trailer Doesn't Reveal Much, But Is Sure To Give You Massive Goosebumps|website=[[Moviepilot]]|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511124217/http://moviepilot.com/posts/3908212|archive-date=May 11, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Blair Witch'' received mixed reviews, with critics noting it as an improvement on ''Book of Shadows'' while criticizing the writing and special effects. While the film grossed $45 million against a budget of $5 million, it was considered a box office disappointment, given that the original film had grossed nearly $250 million in 1999 against a budget of $60,000.<ref name=reviews1>{{cite web|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/blair-witch-bridget-joness-baby-sully-box-office-preview-1201819332/ |title=\u2018Sully\u2019 Squares Off With \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 At Weekend Box Office |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 14, 2016 |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|authorlink=Owen Gleiberman|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/columns/blair-witch-is-the-found-footage-horror-film-over-1201864069/|title=As \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Flops, Is the Found-Footage Horror Film Over?|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 18, 2016|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Dirk|last=Libbey|url=https://cinemablend.com/news/1557760/why-blair-witch-bombed-at-the-box-office|title=Why Blair Witch Bombed At The Box Office|website=Cinemablend|publisher=Cinemablend LLC|location=Portland, Oregon|date=September 20, 2016|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, summaries must be generic and CANNOT EXCEED 400-700 WORDS. IT IS STRONGLY RECOMMENDED NOT TO EXTEND THE SUMMARY ANY FURTHER.-->\nIn 2014, James Donahue finds a video on [[YouTube]] containing an image of a woman he believes to be his sister [[The Blair Witch Project#Cast|Heather]], who [[The Blair Witch Project#Plot|disappeared in 1994]] near [[Burkittsville, Maryland]] while investigating the legend of the [[Blair Witch]]. Believing she is still alive, he heads into the woods, accompanied by his friend Peter Jones, Peter's girlfriend Ashley Bennett, and film student Lisa Arlington, who wants to film James' search as a [[Documentary film|documentary]], ''The Absence of Closure''.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/891264965/the-absence-of-closure/posts/1665045/ |title=The Absence of Closure by Lisa Arlington |website=Kickstarter.com |date=May 12, 2014 |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://absenceofclosure.tumblr.com/ |title=The Absence of Closure |website=Absenceofclosure.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref> Locals Talia and Lane, who found and uploaded the video, join them.\n\nWhile walking through the woods and upon setting up camp for the night, Lane and Talia discuss the disappearance of Heather and her film crew, the 1940-41 murders by Rustin Parr, and other mysterious occurrences, which they ascribe to the Blair Witch. They hear noises during the night, then awaken at 2 p.m. to find strange stick figures hanging from the trees. When Lisa notices [[twine]] in Lane's backpack, he and Talia admit to creating the figures in order to convince the group to believe, but also point out that there is no explanation for the strange noises during the night and sleeping through the day. James and his friends banish Lane and Talia from the group and head out of the woods.\n\nAfter hours of walking, the four surprisingly arrive back at their original campsite. Lisa pilots a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] to obtain their location, but it malfunctions. Ashley becomes sick due to a wound on her foot, forcing the group to camp again. When Peter inspects Ashley's wounded foot, he notices what he thinks may be a parasite inside the wound. Peter leaves the camp for firewood, and is chased by an unknown entity; a tree falls on him, then he disappears.\n\nLane and Talia appear in the night, claiming they have been wandering for five days without a sunrise. Lane believes the camp is a hallucination and runs off, leaving the disheveled and ravenously hungry Talia. The next morning, James and Lisa are stunned to find that it is still dark outside at 7am and discover larger stick figures. Talia sees clumps of her hair tied to one of the figures. Ashley accuses Talia of crafting them and snaps the figure with Talia's hair in half; Talia herself is then snapped in half. An unseen force lifts their tent and the group is separated. Ashley finds the drone and climbs a tree to recover it, but is knocked out and falls from the tree, the unknown entity dragging her away.\n\nA rainstorm ensues as Lisa and James stumble across Rustin Parr's house, which James had previously stated to have been burned down after his execution. James hears someone he thinks is Heather scream upstairs, enters the house and sees Peter standing in the corner. He chases after the figure he believes to be Heather, confronted by a teleporting disheveled figure;{{efn|name=HeatherDonahue|Though glimpsed briefly, the figure indeed appears to be Heather Donahue as she appeared in the closing scenes of ''[[The Blair Witch Project]]'', complete with her torn cardigan and hat. In an interview with [[Adam Wingard]], the film's director, it was later confirmed that the archival footage of Heather Donahue was intentionally meant to portray the Blair Witch in the form of Heather.}} upon its vanishing he barricades himself.\n\nLisa spots a tall, pale, long-limbed creature moving through the trees, and she runs into the house's basement. She finds a hostile Lane who traps her in a tunnel, saying, \u201cyou have to do what she tells you.\u201d She crawls through the tunnel to a different part of the house, where she stabs and kills Lane when he attacks her. Lisa flees when the long-limbed creature emerges from the tunnel and chases her through the house. Lisa runs up to the attic with Lane's camcorder, creating the [[bootstrap paradox|paradox]] video that lured them all to the woods.{{efn|name=ParadoxExplained|Early on in the film, as the group makes its way deep into the woods, Lisa asks Lane about his camera, an older model that she notes uses the exact same tape as the one he claims to have found. The footage Lisa records on Lane\u2019s camera while running through the shack is the same footage Lane found in the woods before the group ever actually went there, implying that they have been caught in a [[time loop]]}}\n\nShe reunites with James in the attic and they try to barricade the door. A bright light shines from outside the building. James tells Lisa to face the corner of the room and desperately apologizes to her before something enters the room. James is tricked into turning around, believing that he hears Heather's voice, and vanishes from sight. Lisa uses Lane's camcorder to view what is behind her and begins walking backward. However, hearing James' apology again, she turns and vanishes, with a flash of a yellowed arm, before her camera falls to the ground. After a few moments, the camera gives out.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Allen McCune]] as James Donahue \n* [[Callie Hernandez]] as Lisa Arlington\n* [[Brandon Scott (actor)|Brandon Scott]] as Peter\n* Corbin Reid as Ashley\n* [[Valorie Curry]] as Talia\n* Wes Robinson as Lane\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nWhile promoting ''[[V/H/S/2]]'' at the [[Sundance Film Festival]], director [[Adam Wingard]] and writer [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]] ran into original ''The Blair Witch Project'' co-filmmaker [[Eduardo S\u00e1nchez (director)|Eduardo S\u00e1nchez]] and producer [[Gregg Hale (producer)|Gregg Hale]], and asked them why there were not any more ''Blair Witch'' films. Although nothing came of the meeting at the time, a few months later, Wingard and Barrett were asked to meet with [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] to potentially work in a secret project.<ref name=\"storybehind\">{{cite web|title=[Interview] The Story Behind the \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Revival|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/exclusives/3404167/interview-story-behind-blair-witch-revival/|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> Barrett recalled that, in the initial pitch meeting, Lionsgate had already crafted a story for a new ''Blair Witch'' film, and simply asked if they would be interested in making it. Barrett said that the \"only thing I really pitched was the other characters; they\u2019d originally conceived the film as more similar to the first film, following its narrative fairly closely, with only three or four characters, I think, but I wanted more characters to give us more scare sequences. I also wanted a unique dynamic within the group from the start, so I pitched the idea of introducing some Burkittsville locals to the group.\"<ref name=\"storybehind\"/>\n\nBarrett would later note that the team found the [[found footage (film technique)|found footage]] genre more challenging, as they have only previously worked with it on the ''V/H/S'' [[Anthology film|anthology movies]].<ref name=\"scaryshoot\">{{cite web|title=[Interview] \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Was Just as Scary to Make, Explains Writer Simon Barrett|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/exclusives/3404168/interview-writer-simon-barrett-says-making-blair-witch-just-scary-make/|website=Bloody Disgusting|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> Barrett noted that with the ''V/H/S'' series, there was an inherent entertainment value, where the segments \"were never meant to feel entirely real\", an element that did not work for the ''Blair Witch'' series.<ref name=\"scaryshoot\"/> Speaking on the issue to [[Bloody Disgusting]], Barrett stated \"even if our scares didn\u2019t work in ''V/H/S'', hopefully people would still be entertained, and if they weren\u2019t, well, another short would start in a few minutes\"; he added that if a scare did not work in ''Blair Witch'', \"we\u2019d have nothing to fall back on, we\u2019d just have failed completely, and publicly.\" To prevent this from happening, Barrett and Winger extensively went over each \"scare\" to discover why it was scary and how the audience would react to it. For some sequences, multiple approaches were tried differently, \"to give us options in the editing room.\"<ref name=\"scaryshoot\"/>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography took place in the spring of 2015, in a set of woods in [[British Columbia]] in Canada. Scenes taking place in the famous Blair Witch House were shot in a sound stage where the House was entirely built.\n\n===Connections to ''The Blair Witch Project''===\nPrior to the film's premiere at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], the fact that the film was a ''Blair Witch'' sequel remained a closely guarded secret,<ref name=\"blairwitchindiewire\">{{cite web|last1=Calvario|first1=Liz|title=''Blair Witch'': How Filmmakers Were Able to Keep the Sequel Under Wraps for Three Years|url=https://indiewire.com/2016/07/blair-witch-filmmakers-keep-sequel-secret-adam-wingard-1201709261/|website=Indiewire|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> as the film was shot under the title ''The Woods''.<ref name=\"blairwitchindiewire\"/> According to the film's writer, Barrett, the film's secrecy was done to prevent backlash among Internet commenters, who the filmmakers felt would react negatively to news of a [[reboot (continuity)|reboot]].<ref name=\"blairwitchsecret\"/>\n\nPrior to the official premiere, Lionsgate went as far as to release a trailer for the film incorporating actual footage, while still keeping the film's lineage a secret.<ref name=\"blairwitchindiewire\"/>  The film was still publicly known as ''The Woods'' even at Comic-Con, prior to its first screening, with [[io9]] reporting that the initial theater for the screening was filled with posters for the fake film. After the screening (during which audiences realized that the film was a sequel), all the promotional material in the theater was changed to reflect the film's actual title.<ref name=\"blairwitchsecret\">{{cite web|last1=Lussler|first1=Germain|title=Why the New ''Blair Witch'' Movie Had to Be Kept Secret|url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/why-the-new-blair-witch-movie-had-to-be-kept-secret-1786017592|website=io9|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 11, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewrap.com/toronto-film-festival-adds-movies-by-leonardo-dicaprio-werner-herzog-marlon-brando/|title=Toronto Film Festival Adds Movies by Leonardo DiCaprio, Werner Herzog, Marlon Brando|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=September 9, 2016|accessdate=August 9, 2016}}</ref> and was theatrically released on September 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/05/lionsgate-nerve-the-woods-release-dates-1201752448/|title=Lionsgate Moves YA Title ''Nerve'' Into Summer, Schedules ''The Woods''|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=July 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Blair Witch'' grossed $20.8 million in North America and $24.4 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $45.2 million, against a production budget of $5 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released on September 16, 2016, and was initially projected to gross at least $20 million with a chance to get as high as $26 million in its opening weekend, from 3,121 theaters.<ref name=\"VVV\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/box-office-sully-blair-witch-bridget-jones-1201859604/|title=Box Office: \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Looks to Scare Off \u2018Sully,\u2019 \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019s Baby\u2019|author=Dave McNarry|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pro.boxoffice.com/weekend-forecast-blair-witch-bridget-joness-baby-hillsong-let-hope-rise-snowden/|title=Weekend Forecast: \u2018Blair Witch,\u2019 \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019s Baby,\u2019 \u2018Hillsong \u2013 Let Hope Rise\u2019 & \u2018Snowden\u2019|author=|work=pro.boxoffice.com|date=September 14, 2016}}</ref> Lionsgate's expectations were more conservative, however, with a projected $15\u201318 million opening, although rival studios were predicting significantly higher numbers, noting how horror films saw solid performances throughout 2016, including ''[[Lights Out (2016 film)|Lights Out]]'', ''[[The Conjuring 2]]'', ''[[The Purge: Election Year]]'', ''[[The Shallows (film)|The Shallows]]'' and ''[[Don't Breathe]]''.<ref name=\"VVV\"/> However, after grossing $765,000 from its Thursday previews and $4.1 million on its first day, opening projections were lowered to $10 million. It ended up grossing $9.7 million in its opening weekend, below expectations and the lowest opening weekend of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/bridget-jones-blair-witch-snowden-sully-weekend-box-office-renee-zellweger-1201820827/ |title=\u2018Sully\u2019 Burns \u2018Blair Witch\u2019, \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019 & \u2018Snowden\u2019 At The Box Office Stake \u2013 Friday Evening Update |work= [[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> The film was considered a box office disappointment by analysts.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe film received a day-and-date release in many countries in conjunction with its North American debut.<ref name=\"DEADproj\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/sully-glides-in-with-1-35m-for-warner-bros-thursday-box-office-1201815274/|title=\u2018Sully\u2019 Lands At $35M, \u2018Bough\u2019 Breaks With $14.2M \u2013 Monday B.O. Final|author=Anita Busch and Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 12, 2016|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film cost $5 million to produce, with an additional $20 million spent on promotion, advertising and marketing costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/blair-witch-bridget-joness-baby-sully-box-office-preview-1201819332/|title=Can \u2018Sully\u2019 Crucify \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 At The Weekend B.O.? \u2013 Preview|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 14, 2016|accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Blair Witch'' received mixed reviews, with critics noting it as an improvement on ''Book of Shadows'' while criticizing the writing and special effects.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/09/19/blair-witch-2-director-defends-movie/|title=Blair Witch 2 director defends his movie after new sequel stumbles |author=Nolfi, Joey |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 19, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/09/blair-witch-gets-lost-in-the-woods-again/500276/|title=Blair Witch Gets Lost in the Woods (Again) |author=Orr, Christopher |website=[[The Atlantic]] |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"rock\">{{cite web |url=http://rockrivertimes.com/2016/09/20/blair-witch-lacks-any-real-scares/ |title=Blair Witch lacks any real scares |author=Simpson, Thomas |website=[[Rock River Times]] |date=September 20, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922124317/http://rockrivertimes.com/2016/09/20/blair-witch-lacks-any-real-scares/ |archive-date=September 22, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 37% based on 216 reviews, with an average rating of 5.18/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Blair Witch'' doles out a handful of effective scares, but aside from a few new twists, it mainly offers a belated rehash of the original \u2013 and far more memorable \u2013 first film.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Blair Witch (2016)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blair_witch/|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 47 out of 100, based on 41 critics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blair Witch reviews|url=https://metacritic.com/movie/blair-witch-2016|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"D+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://m.cinemascore.com |archive-url=https://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20170916153548/https://m.cinemascore.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2017-09-16 |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com }}</ref>  According to ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Joey Nolfi, while ''Blair Witch'' is generally regarded as an improvement over ''[[Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2]]'', \"moviegoers and film journalists essentially told [''Blair Witch''] to stand in the corner...critical reviews and audience exit polling...are still some of the worst of any 2016 release thus far.\"<ref name=\"ew\"/>\n\nMichael Roffman of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' wrote that \"Nothing [about the film] is scary, nothing is remotely disturbing, and there\u2019s this boring familiarity to the proceedings, namely because it\u2019s more or less a beat-by-beat remake of the original.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/09/film-review-blair-witch/|title=Film Review: Blair Witch |author=Roffman, Michael |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=September 14, 2016 |accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'''s Leslie Felperin criticized the film, commenting that it is \"a dull retread rather than a full-on reinvention,\" enlarging the cast numbers this time but sticking to the same basic beats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/review/blair-witch-review-927536 |title='Blair Witch': Film Review TIFF 2016 |author=Felperin, Leslie |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 11, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> Scott Tobias of ''[[GQ]]'' felt that the makers of ''Blair Witch'' made a poor decision by making the film less subtle than the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/blair-witch-review |title=Blair Witch Review: It\u2019s No Blair Witch Project |author=Tobias, Scott|website=[[GQ]] |date=September 13, 2016 |accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref> Thomas Simpson of the ''[[Rock River Times]]'' said that the film \"lacks any real scares\" and that, after watching it, \"you shouldn\u2019t have any issues turning the light off at night.\"<ref name=\"rock\"/> The ''[[New York Post]]''{{'}}s [[Kyle Smith]] condemned the film by saying that \"the take-away from ''Blair Witch'' is not terror, but sorrow,\" and gave it 1.5 stars out of 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/09/15/poor-blair-witch-she-deserves-a-better-movie/ |title=Poor Blair Witch \u2014 she deserves a better movie |author=Smith, Kyle|website=New York Post |date=September 15, 2016 |accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nJosh Kurp of [[Uproxx]] gave the film a mixed review, saying \"''Blair Witch'' is scary, but it lacks surprise, and without surprise, you\u2019re left with a bunch of kind-of annoying people shakily filming themselves wandering the woods and reacting to loud noises.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/blair-witch-review/ |title=\u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Is Too Afraid To Do Anything New |work= [[Uproxx]]}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]] gave the film three out of five stars in a review for ''[[The Guardian]]'', calling it \"efficient if unadventurous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news | last = Kermode | first = Mark | title =Blair Witch review \u2013 efficient horror sequel | work =[[The Guardian]]| date = September 18, 2016 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/sep/18/blair-witch-new-film-review-mark-kermode | accessdate = October 14, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''{{'}}s Jordan Hoffman felt that the film was inferior to ''[[You're Next]]'', a previous film by Wingard and writer [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]], and said  ''Blair Witch''{{'}}s \"jump-scares [will] make for a fun night at the movies, but it\u2019s like chomping on [[White Castle (restaurant)|White Castle]] hamburgers\u2014when this creative team has previously served us a prime rib.\"<ref name=\"fair\">{{cite news | last = Hoffman | first = Jordan | title =Blair Witch Has Scares, but It Never Quite Gets Out of the Woods | work =[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]| date = September 12, 2016 | url = http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/09/blair-witch-2016-review | accessdate = October 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nConversely, [[IGN]] reviewer Chris Tilly declared that ''Blair Witch'' is \"so good it'll make you forget that ''Book of Shadows'' ever happened.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ign.com/articles/2016/09/12/blair-witch-review |title=Blair Witch Review |author=Tilly, Chris |website=IGN |date=September 12, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> Mark Eccleston of ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' wrote that the film has \"genuine, jarring scares...and an unsettling late surprise that makes it well worth popping to you nearest multiplex to have the holy crap scared out of you.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/celebrity/2016/09/16/blair-witch-movie-review|title=FILM REVIEW: Just how scary is the new Blair Witch? |author=Eccleston, Mark |website=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref> [[Bloody Disgusting]]'s [[Brad Miska]] writes, \"''Blair Witch'' is that game-changer horror fans desperately have been waiting for.\" Miska gave the film a 4.5 out of 5 rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3399467/review-blair-witch-the-woods-horror-game-changer-will-completely-wreck/ |title=[Review] 'Blair Witch' |author=Miska, Brad |publisher=Bloody Disgusting |date=July 22, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> and included it in his list of the \"Best Horror Films of 2016\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3415487/mr-disgustings-top-horror-films-2016/2/ |title=Mr. Disgusting Picks the Best Horror Films of 2016! |author=Miska, Brad |publisher=Bloody Disgusting |date=December 26, 2016 |accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Blair Witch (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Adam Wingard]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 16, 2016\n| recorded   = January 23, 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Stage & Screen\n| length     = 32:20\n| label      = [[Lakeshore Records]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack was released on September 16, 2016 via [[Lakeshore Records]], concurrent with the film's release. The score is a collaboration of director Wingard with electronic music producer [[Robert Rich (musician)|Robert Rich]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Calvario|first1=Liz|title=\u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Soundtrack: Listen to Director Adam Wingard\u2019s Creepy Ambient Music|url=https://indiewire.com/2016/09/blair-witch-soundtrack-listen-adam-wingard-score-1201727806/|publisher=[[indiewire.com]]|accessdate=October 28, 2016|date=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n# \"Black Hills Forest\"\n# \"Rustin Parr\"\n# \"Camp Fire\"\n# \"Panic Attack\"\n# \"Blair Witch\"\n# \"Lane and Talia\"\n# \"The Project\"\n# \"Invocation of Evil\"\n# \"No Trespassing\"\n# \"The House in the Woods\"\n\n;Additional music\n# \"Hakmarrja\"&nbsp;\u2013 [[N.K.V.D (metal band)|N.K.V.D]]<ref name=\"what-song.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.what-song.com/Movies/Soundtrack/2053/Blair-Witch |title=Blair Witch (2016): Soundtrack and Complete List of Songs |publisher=WhatSong |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"lgukpublicity.co.uk\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lgukpublicity.co.uk/uk/images/Prodnotes/BLAIR_WITCH_UK_Production_Notes_FINAL_050916.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920163255/http://www.lgukpublicity.co.uk/uk/images/Prodnotes/BLAIR_WITCH_UK_Production_Notes_FINAL_050916.pdf |archive-date=September 20, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>   \n# \"Pagan Dance Move\"&nbsp;\u2013 [[Arnaud Rebotini]]<ref name=\"what-song.com\"/><ref name=\"lgukpublicity.co.uk\"/>\n# \"Rien \u00e0 Paris\"&nbsp;\u2013 Liz & L\u00e1szl\u00f3<ref name=\"what-song.com\"/><ref name=\"lgukpublicity.co.uk\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring drones]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.blairwitch.movie/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1540011|Blair Witch}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|blair_witch|Blair Witch}}\n* {{mojo title|woods2016|Blair Witch}}\n* {{Metacritic film|blair-witch|Blair Witch}}\n\n{{Blair Witch}}\n{{Adam Wingard}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blair Witch (film)}}\n[[Category:2010s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2016 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Alternative sequel films]]\n[[Category:Blair Witch (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Camcorder films]]\n[[Category:Drone films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about death]]\n[[Category:Films about film directors and producers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Adam Wingard]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2014]]\n[[Category:Films set in forests]]\n[[Category:Films set in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|The Blair Witch Project}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name               = Blair Witch\n| image              = Blair Witch 2016 poster.png\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Theatrical release poster\n| director           = [[Adam Wingard]]\n| producer           = {{plainlist|\n* [[Roy Lee]]\n* Steven Schneider\n* [[Keith Calder]]\n* Jess Calder\n}}\n| writer             = [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]]\n| starring           = {{plainlist|\n* [[James Allen McCune]]\n* [[Callie Hernandez]]\n* Brandon Scott\n* Corbin Reid\n* [[Valorie Curry]]\n* Wes Robinson\n}}\n| music              = Adam Wingard\n| cinematography     = Robby Baumgartner\t\n| editing            = Louis Cioffi\n| studio = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n* [[Vertigo Entertainment]]\n* Room 101\n* Snoot Entertainment\n}}\n| distributor          = Lionsgate\n| released             = {{Film date|2016|7|22|[[San Diego Comic-Con]]|2016|9|16|United States}}\n| runtime              = 89 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 89:03 --><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/blair-witch-film|title=''BLAIR WITCH'' (15)|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=August 17, 2016|accessdate=August 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| country              = {{plainlist|* United States\n* Canada<ref name=\"LUMIERE\">{{cite web|url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=67903 |title=Film: Blair Witch |website=[[LUMIERE]]|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| language             = English\n| budget               = $5 million<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doty|first1=Meriah|title=Will \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Beat \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019s Baby\u2019 in Box Office Battle of Long-Delayed Sequels?|url=https://thewrap.com/blair-witch-bridget-jones-baby-box-office/|website=[[TheWrap]]|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref><ref name=BOM/>\n| gross                = $45.2 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=woods2016.htm |title=Blair Witch (2016) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Blair Witch''''' is a 2016 American [[supernatural horror film]] directed by [[Adam Wingard]] and written by [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Nordine|url=https://indiewire.com/article/the-woods-trailer-adam-wingard-found-footage-horror-20160510|title=''The Woods'' Trailer: Adam Wingard Takes Us Camping in New Found-Footage Horror Flick|website=[[Indiewire]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref> It is the third film in the ''[[Blair Witch]]'' series and a direct sequel to the 1999 film ''[[The Blair Witch Project]]'', ignoring the events of its 2000 follow-up film ''[[Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2]]'', given the events of that film being a [[play within a play|film within a film]].{{efn|name=BookOfShadows|In the tie-in documentary to ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'', ''Shadow of the Blair Witch'', the events of ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'' are presented in-universe as a film adaptation based on the \"Black Hills murders\" that took place shortly after the events of ''The Blair Witch Project''. This documentary presents the events of ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'' as a film within a film. ''Shadow of the Blair Witch'' follows \"the real Jeff Patterson\u2019s defense team as the case prepares for trial and as the public reacts to plans to fictionalize the case\u2019s events for the big screen from the defense's point-of-view. Protests of the film ''Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2'' are discussed within the documentary coming from both the families of those involved with the case and from the Wiccan community as a whole. Rachel Moskowitz and Andre Brooks respectively portray the \"real\" Kim Diamond and Jeffrey Patterson within the documentary.}} ''Blair Witch'' stars [[James Allen McCune]], [[Callie Hernandez]], Brandon Scott, Corbin Reid, [[Valorie Curry]], and Wes Robinson. The film, shot in a [[Found footage (film technique)|found footage]] style, follows a group of college students and their local guides who venture into the Black Hills Forest in Maryland to uncover the mysteries surrounding the prior disappearance of [[Heather Donahue]], the sister of one of the characters.\n\nDevelopment of the film began in September 2009, when creators of the franchise [[Daniel Myrick]] and [[Eduardo S\u00e1nchez (director)|Eduardo S\u00e1nchez]] announced their intent to produce a third ''Blair Witch'' film. The film was a sequel to the first film, would potentially contain the actors from the first film in some context, and would not reference any of the events from ''Book of Shadows''. In 2011, S\u00e1nchez remarked that further development on a sequel depended on getting [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] to approve the idea and for his and Myrick's schedule to match up.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The film went into [[development hell]], and later the script was trowed aside. In 2013, a third ''Blair Witch'' film was again in talks, with Wingard and Barrett being hired to work on a new script.\n\nInitially, the film's connection to the ''Blair Witch'' franchise was kept secret, with the film having been shot under the fake title, ''The Woods''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Roffman|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/07/adam-wingards-the-woods-is-actually-a-sequel-to-the-blair-witch-project/|title=Adam Wingard's ''The Woods'' is actually a sequel to ''The Blair Witch Project''|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|publisher=Consequence Holdings, LLC|location=Chicago, Illinois|date=July 23, 2016|language=en-US|access-date=July 25, 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, it was revealed at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]] that the film marketed with the faux-title ''The Woods'' actually turned out to be the sequel ''Blair Witch''.\n\nThe film premiered at San Diego Comic-Con on July 22, 2016 and was screened at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 11, before being theatrically released in the United States on September 16, by Lionsgate.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michelle|last=Smith|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/3908212|title=''The Woods'' Trailer Doesn't Reveal Much, But Is Sure To Give You Massive Goosebumps|website=[[Moviepilot]]|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=May 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511124217/http://moviepilot.com/posts/3908212|archive-date=May 11, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Blair Witch'' received mixed reviews, with critics noting it as an improvement on ''Book of Shadows'' while criticizing the writing and special effects. While the film grossed $45 million against a budget of $5 million, it was considered a box office disappointment, given that the original film had grossed nearly $250 million in 1999 against a budget of $60,000.<ref name=reviews1>{{cite web|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/blair-witch-bridget-joness-baby-sully-box-office-preview-1201819332/ |title=\u2018Sully\u2019 Squares Off With \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 At Weekend Box Office |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 14, 2016 |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|authorlink=Owen Gleiberman|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/columns/blair-witch-is-the-found-footage-horror-film-over-1201864069/|title=As \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Flops, Is the Found-Footage Horror Film Over?|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 18, 2016|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Dirk|last=Libbey|url=https://cinemablend.com/news/1557760/why-blair-witch-bombed-at-the-box-office|title=Why Blair Witch Bombed At The Box Office|website=Cinemablend|publisher=Cinemablend LLC|location=Portland, Oregon|date=September 20, 2016|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, summaries must be generic and CANNOT EXCEED 400-700 WORDS. IT IS STRONGLY RECOMMENDED NOT TO EXTEND THE SUMMARY ANY FURTHER.-->\nIn 2014, James Donahue finds a video on [[YouTube]] containing an image of a woman he believes to be his sister [[The Blair Witch Project#Cast|Heather]], who [[The Blair Witch Project#Plot|disappeared in 1994]] near [[Burkittsville, Maryland]] while investigating the legend of the [[Blair Witch]]. Believing she is still alive, he heads into the woods, accompanied by his friend Peter Jones, Peter's girlfriend Ashley Bennett, and film student Lisa Arlington, who wants to film James' search as a [[Documentary film|documentary]], ''The Absence of Closure''.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/891264965/the-absence-of-closure/posts/1665045/ |title=The Absence of Closure by Lisa Arlington |website=Kickstarter.com |date=May 12, 2014 |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://absenceofclosure.tumblr.com/ |title=The Absence of Closure |website=Absenceofclosure.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=January 7, 2017}}</ref> Locals Talia and Lane, who found and uploaded the video, join them.\n\nWhile walking through the woods and upon setting up camp for the night, Lane and Talia discuss the disappearance of Heather and her film crew, the 1940-41 murders by Rustin Parr, and other mysterious occurrences, which they ascribe to the Blair Witch. They hear noises during the night, then awaken at 2 p.m. to find strange stick figures hanging from the trees. When Lisa notices [[twine]] in Lane's backpack, he and Talia admit to creating the figures in order to convince the group to believe, but also point out that there is no explanation for the strange noises during the night and sleeping through the day. James and his friends banish Lane and Talia from the group and head out of the woods.\n\nAfter hours of walking, the four surprisingly arrive back at their original campsite. Lisa pilots a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] to obtain their location, but it malfunctions. Ashley becomes sick due to a wound on her foot, forcing the group to camp again. When Peter inspects Ashley's wounded foot, he notices what he thinks may be a parasite inside the wound. Peter leaves the camp for firewood, and is chased by an unknown entity; a tree falls on him, then he disappears.\n\nLane and Talia appear in the night, claiming they have been wandering for five days without a sunrise. Lane believes the camp is a hallucination and runs off, leaving the disheveled and ravenously hungry Talia. The next morning, James and Lisa are stunned to find that it is still dark outside at 7am and discover larger stick figures. Talia sees clumps of her hair tied to one of the figures. Ashley accuses Talia of crafting them and snaps the figure with Talia's hair in half; Talia herself is then snapped in half. An unseen force lifts their tent and the group is separated. Ashley finds the drone and climbs a tree to recover it, but is knocked out and falls from the tree, the unknown entity dragging her away.\n\nA rainstorm ensues as Lisa and James stumble across Rustin Parr's house, which James had previously stated to have been burned down after his execution. James hears someone he thinks is Heather scream upstairs, enters the house and sees Peter standing in the corner. He chases after the figure he believes to be Heather, confronted by a teleporting disheveled figure;{{efn|name=HeatherDonahue|Though glimpsed briefly, the figure indeed appears to be Heather Donahue as she appeared in the closing scenes of ''[[The Blair Witch Project]]'', complete with her torn cardigan and hat. In an interview with [[Adam Wingard]], the film's director, it was later confirmed that the archival footage of Heather Donahue was intentionally meant to portray the Blair Witch in the form of Heather.}} upon its vanishing he barricades himself.\n\nLisa spots a tall, pale, long-limbed creature moving through the trees, and she runs into the house's basement. She finds a hostile Lane who traps her in a tunnel, saying, \u201cyou have to do what she tells you.\u201d She crawls through the tunnel to a different part of the house, where she stabs and kills Lane when he attacks her. Lisa flees when the long-limbed creature emerges from the tunnel and chases her through the house. Lisa runs up to the attic with Lane's camcorder, creating the [[bootstrap paradox|paradox]] video that lured them all to the woods.{{efn|name=ParadoxExplained|Early on in the film, as the group makes its way deep into the woods, Lisa asks Lane about his camera, an older model that she notes uses the exact same tape as the one he claims to have found. The footage Lisa records on Lane\u2019s camera while running through the shack is the same footage Lane found in the woods before the group ever actually went there, implying that they have been caught in a [[time loop]]}}\n\nShe reunites with James in the attic and they try to barricade the door. A bright light shines from outside the building. James tells Lisa to face the corner of the room and desperately apologizes to her before something enters the room. James is tricked into turning around, believing that he hears Heather's voice, and vanishes from sight. Lisa uses Lane's camcorder to view what is behind her and begins walking backward. However, hearing James' apology again, she turns and vanishes, with a flash of a yellowed arm, before her camera falls to the ground. After a few moments, the camera gives out.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[James Allen McCune]] as James Donahue \n* [[Callie Hernandez]] as Lisa Arlington\n* [[Brandon Scott (actor)|Brandon Scott]] as Peter\n* Corbin Reid as Ashley\n* [[Valorie Curry]] as Talia\n* Wes Robinson as Lane\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nWhile promoting ''[[V/H/S/2]]'' at the [[Sundance Film Festival]], director [[Adam Wingard]] and writer [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]] ran into original ''The Blair Witch Project'' co-filmmaker [[Eduardo S\u00e1nchez (director)|Eduardo S\u00e1nchez]] and producer [[Gregg Hale (producer)|Gregg Hale]], and asked them why there were not any more ''Blair Witch'' films. Although nothing came of the meeting at the time, a few months later, Wingard and Barrett were asked to meet with [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] to potentially work in a secret project.<ref name=\"storybehind\">{{cite web|title=[Interview] The Story Behind the \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Revival|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/exclusives/3404167/interview-story-behind-blair-witch-revival/|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> Barrett recalled that, in the initial pitch meeting, Lionsgate had already crafted a story for a new ''Blair Witch'' film, and simply asked if they would be interested in making it. Barrett said that the \"only thing I really pitched was the other characters; they\u2019d originally conceived the film as more similar to the first film, following its narrative fairly closely, with only three or four characters, I think, but I wanted more characters to give us more scare sequences. I also wanted a unique dynamic within the group from the start, so I pitched the idea of introducing some Burkittsville locals to the group.\"<ref name=\"storybehind\"/>\n\nBarrett would later note that the team found the [[found footage (film technique)|found footage]] genre more challenging, as they have only previously worked with it on the ''V/H/S'' [[Anthology film|anthology movies]].<ref name=\"scaryshoot\">{{cite web|title=[Interview] \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Was Just as Scary to Make, Explains Writer Simon Barrett|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/exclusives/3404168/interview-writer-simon-barrett-says-making-blair-witch-just-scary-make/|website=Bloody Disgusting|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref> Barrett noted that with the ''V/H/S'' series, there was an inherent entertainment value, where the segments \"were never meant to feel entirely real\", an element that did not work for the ''Blair Witch'' series.<ref name=\"scaryshoot\"/> Speaking on the issue to [[Bloody Disgusting]], Barrett stated \"even if our scares didn\u2019t work in ''V/H/S'', hopefully people would still be entertained, and if they weren\u2019t, well, another short would start in a few minutes\"; he added that if a scare did not work in ''Blair Witch'', \"we\u2019d have nothing to fall back on, we\u2019d just have failed completely, and publicly.\" To prevent this from happening, Barrett and Winger extensively went over each \"scare\" to discover why it was scary and how the audience would react to it. For some sequences, multiple approaches were tried differently, \"to give us options in the editing room.\"<ref name=\"scaryshoot\"/>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography took place in the spring of 2015, in a set of woods in [[British Columbia]] in Canada. Scenes taking place in the famous Blair Witch House were shot in a sound stage where the House was entirely built.\n\n===Connections to ''The Blair Witch Project''===\nPrior to the film's premiere at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], the fact that the film was a ''Blair Witch'' sequel remained a closely guarded secret,<ref name=\"blairwitchindiewire\">{{cite web|last1=Calvario|first1=Liz|title=''Blair Witch'': How Filmmakers Were Able to Keep the Sequel Under Wraps for Three Years|url=https://indiewire.com/2016/07/blair-witch-filmmakers-keep-sequel-secret-adam-wingard-1201709261/|website=Indiewire|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref> as the film was shot under the title ''The Woods''.<ref name=\"blairwitchindiewire\"/> According to the film's writer, Barrett, the film's secrecy was done to prevent backlash among Internet commenters, who the filmmakers felt would react negatively to news of a [[reboot (continuity)|reboot]].<ref name=\"blairwitchsecret\"/>\n\nPrior to the official premiere, Lionsgate went as far as to release a trailer for the film incorporating actual footage, while still keeping the film's lineage a secret.<ref name=\"blairwitchindiewire\"/>  The film was still publicly known as ''The Woods'' even at Comic-Con, prior to its first screening, with [[io9]] reporting that the initial theater for the screening was filled with posters for the fake film. After the screening (during which audiences realized that the film was a sequel), all the promotional material in the theater was changed to reflect the film's actual title.<ref name=\"blairwitchsecret\">{{cite web|last1=Lussler|first1=Germain|title=Why the New ''Blair Witch'' Movie Had to Be Kept Secret|url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/why-the-new-blair-witch-movie-had-to-be-kept-secret-1786017592|website=io9|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 11, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewrap.com/toronto-film-festival-adds-movies-by-leonardo-dicaprio-werner-herzog-marlon-brando/|title=Toronto Film Festival Adds Movies by Leonardo DiCaprio, Werner Herzog, Marlon Brando|website=[[The Wrap]]|first=Steve|last=Pond|date=September 9, 2016|accessdate=August 9, 2016}}</ref> and was theatrically released on September 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/05/lionsgate-nerve-the-woods-release-dates-1201752448/|title=Lionsgate Moves YA Title ''Nerve'' Into Summer, Schedules ''The Woods''|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=July 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Blair Witch'' grossed $20.8 million in North America and $24.4 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $45.2 million, against a production budget of $5 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released on September 16, 2016, and was initially projected to gross at least $20 million with a chance to get as high as $26 million in its opening weekend, from 3,121 theaters.<ref name=\"VVV\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/box-office-sully-blair-witch-bridget-jones-1201859604/|title=Box Office: \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Looks to Scare Off \u2018Sully,\u2019 \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019s Baby\u2019|author=Dave McNarry|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pro.boxoffice.com/weekend-forecast-blair-witch-bridget-joness-baby-hillsong-let-hope-rise-snowden/|title=Weekend Forecast: \u2018Blair Witch,\u2019 \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019s Baby,\u2019 \u2018Hillsong \u2013 Let Hope Rise\u2019 & \u2018Snowden\u2019|author=|work=pro.boxoffice.com|date=September 14, 2016}}</ref> Lionsgate's expectations were more conservative, however, with a projected $15\u201318 million opening, although rival studios were predicting significantly higher numbers, noting how horror films saw solid performances throughout 2016, including ''[[Lights Out (2016 film)|Lights Out]]'', ''[[The Conjuring 2]]'', ''[[The Purge: Election Year]]'', ''[[The Shallows (film)|The Shallows]]'' and ''[[Don't Breathe]]''.<ref name=\"VVV\"/> However, after grossing $765,000 from its Thursday previews and $4.1 million on its first day, opening projections were lowered to $10 million. It ended up grossing $9.7 million in its opening weekend, below expectations and the lowest opening weekend of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/bridget-jones-blair-witch-snowden-sully-weekend-box-office-renee-zellweger-1201820827/ |title=\u2018Sully\u2019 Burns \u2018Blair Witch\u2019, \u2018Bridget Jones\u2019 & \u2018Snowden\u2019 At The Box Office Stake \u2013 Friday Evening Update |work= [[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> The film was considered a box office disappointment by analysts.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe film received a day-and-date release in many countries in conjunction with its North American debut.<ref name=\"DEADproj\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/sully-glides-in-with-1-35m-for-warner-bros-thursday-box-office-1201815274/|title=\u2018Sully\u2019 Lands At $35M, \u2018Bough\u2019 Breaks With $14.2M \u2013 Monday B.O. Final|author=Anita Busch and Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 12, 2016|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film cost $5 million to produce, with an additional $20 million spent on promotion, advertising and marketing costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/blair-witch-bridget-joness-baby-sully-box-office-preview-1201819332/|title=Can \u2018Sully\u2019 Crucify \u2018Blair Witch\u2019 At The Weekend B.O.? \u2013 Preview|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 14, 2016|accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n''Blair Witch'' received mixed reviews, with critics noting it as an improvement on ''Book of Shadows'' while criticizing the writing and special effects.<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2016/09/19/blair-witch-2-director-defends-movie/|title=Blair Witch 2 director defends his movie after new sequel stumbles |author=Nolfi, Joey |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 19, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/09/blair-witch-gets-lost-in-the-woods-again/500276/|title=Blair Witch Gets Lost in the Woods (Again) |author=Orr, Christopher |website=[[The Atlantic]] |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"rock\">{{cite web |url=http://rockrivertimes.com/2016/09/20/blair-witch-lacks-any-real-scares/ |title=Blair Witch lacks any real scares |author=Simpson, Thomas |website=[[Rock River Times]] |date=September 20, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922124317/http://rockrivertimes.com/2016/09/20/blair-witch-lacks-any-real-scares/ |archive-date=September 22, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 36% based on 215 reviews, with an average rating of 5.18/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Blair Witch'' doles out a handful of effective scares, but aside from a few new twists, it mainly offers a belated rehash of the original \u2013 and far more memorable \u2013 first film.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Blair Witch (2016)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blair_witch/|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 47 out of 100, based on 41 critics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blair Witch reviews|url=https://metacritic.com/movie/blair-witch-2016|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"D+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://m.cinemascore.com |archive-url=https://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20170916153548/https://m.cinemascore.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2017-09-16 |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com }}</ref>  According to ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Joey Nolfi, while ''Blair Witch'' is generally regarded as an improvement over ''[[Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2]]'', \"moviegoers and film journalists essentially told [''Blair Witch''] to stand in the corner...critical reviews and audience exit polling...are still some of the worst of any 2016 release thus far.\"<ref name=\"ew\"/>\n\nMichael Roffman of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' wrote that \"Nothing [about the film] is scary, nothing is remotely disturbing, and there\u2019s this boring familiarity to the proceedings, namely because it\u2019s more or less a beat-by-beat remake of the original.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/09/film-review-blair-witch/|title=Film Review: Blair Witch |author=Roffman, Michael |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=September 14, 2016 |accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'''s Leslie Felperin criticized the film, commenting that it is \"a dull retread rather than a full-on reinvention,\" enlarging the cast numbers this time but sticking to the same basic beats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/review/blair-witch-review-927536 |title='Blair Witch': Film Review TIFF 2016 |author=Felperin, Leslie |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 11, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> Scott Tobias of ''[[GQ]]'' felt that the makers of ''Blair Witch'' made a poor decision by making the film less subtle than the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/blair-witch-review |title=Blair Witch Review: It\u2019s No Blair Witch Project |author=Tobias, Scott|website=[[GQ]] |date=September 13, 2016 |accessdate=October 14, 2016}}</ref> Thomas Simpson of the ''[[Rock River Times]]'' said that the film \"lacks any real scares\" and that, after watching it, \"you shouldn\u2019t have any issues turning the light off at night.\"<ref name=\"rock\"/> The ''[[New York Post]]''{{'}}s [[Kyle Smith]] condemned the film by saying that \"the take-away from ''Blair Witch'' is not terror, but sorrow,\" and gave it 1.5 stars out of 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/09/15/poor-blair-witch-she-deserves-a-better-movie/ |title=Poor Blair Witch \u2014 she deserves a better movie |author=Smith, Kyle|website=New York Post |date=September 15, 2016 |accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nJosh Kurp of [[Uproxx]] gave the film a mixed review, saying \"''Blair Witch'' is scary, but it lacks surprise, and without surprise, you\u2019re left with a bunch of kind-of annoying people shakily filming themselves wandering the woods and reacting to loud noises.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/blair-witch-review/ |title=\u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Is Too Afraid To Do Anything New |work= [[Uproxx]]}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]] gave the film three out of five stars in a review for ''[[The Guardian]]'', calling it \"efficient if unadventurous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news | last = Kermode | first = Mark | title =Blair Witch review \u2013 efficient horror sequel | work =[[The Guardian]]| date = September 18, 2016 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/sep/18/blair-witch-new-film-review-mark-kermode | accessdate = October 14, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''{{'}}s Jordan Hoffman felt that the film was inferior to ''[[You're Next]]'', a previous film by Wingard and writer [[Simon Barrett (filmmaker)|Simon Barrett]], and said  ''Blair Witch''{{'}}s \"jump-scares [will] make for a fun night at the movies, but it\u2019s like chomping on [[White Castle (restaurant)|White Castle]] hamburgers\u2014when this creative team has previously served us a prime rib.\"<ref name=\"fair\">{{cite news | last = Hoffman | first = Jordan | title =Blair Witch Has Scares, but It Never Quite Gets Out of the Woods | work =[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]| date = September 12, 2016 | url = http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/09/blair-witch-2016-review | accessdate = October 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nConversely, [[IGN]] reviewer Chris Tilly declared that ''Blair Witch'' is \"so good it'll make you forget that ''Book of Shadows'' ever happened.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ign.com/articles/2016/09/12/blair-witch-review |title=Blair Witch Review |author=Tilly, Chris |website=IGN |date=September 12, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> Mark Eccleston of ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' wrote that the film has \"genuine, jarring scares...and an unsettling late surprise that makes it well worth popping to you nearest multiplex to have the holy crap scared out of you.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/celebrity/2016/09/16/blair-witch-movie-review|title=FILM REVIEW: Just how scary is the new Blair Witch? |author=Eccleston, Mark |website=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref> [[Bloody Disgusting]]'s [[Brad Miska]] writes, \"''Blair Witch'' is that game-changer horror fans desperately have been waiting for.\" Miska gave the film a 4.5 out of 5 rating,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3399467/review-blair-witch-the-woods-horror-game-changer-will-completely-wreck/ |title=[Review] 'Blair Witch' |author=Miska, Brad |publisher=Bloody Disgusting |date=July 22, 2016 |accessdate=September 15, 2016}}</ref> and included it in his list of the \"Best Horror Films of 2016\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3415487/mr-disgustings-top-horror-films-2016/2/ |title=Mr. Disgusting Picks the Best Horror Films of 2016! |author=Miska, Brad |publisher=Bloody Disgusting |date=December 26, 2016 |accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Blair Witch (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Adam Wingard]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 16, 2016\n| recorded   = January 23, 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = Stage & Screen\n| length     = 32:20\n| label      = [[Lakeshore Records]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack was released on September 16, 2016 via [[Lakeshore Records]], concurrent with the film's release. The score is a collaboration of director Wingard with electronic music producer [[Robert Rich (musician)|Robert Rich]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Calvario|first1=Liz|title=\u2018Blair Witch\u2019 Soundtrack: Listen to Director Adam Wingard\u2019s Creepy Ambient Music|url=https://indiewire.com/2016/09/blair-witch-soundtrack-listen-adam-wingard-score-1201727806/|publisher=[[indiewire.com]]|accessdate=October 28, 2016|date=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n# \"Black Hills Forest\"\n# \"Rustin Parr\"\n# \"Camp Fire\"\n# \"Panic Attack\"\n# \"Blair Witch\"\n# \"Lane and Talia\"\n# \"The Project\"\n# \"Invocation of Evil\"\n# \"No Trespassing\"\n# \"The House in the Woods\"\n\n;Additional music\n# \"Hakmarrja\"&nbsp;\u2013 [[N.K.V.D (metal band)|N.K.V.D]]<ref name=\"what-song.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.what-song.com/Movies/Soundtrack/2053/Blair-Witch |title=Blair Witch (2016): Soundtrack and Complete List of Songs |publisher=WhatSong |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"lgukpublicity.co.uk\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.lgukpublicity.co.uk/uk/images/Prodnotes/BLAIR_WITCH_UK_Production_Notes_FINAL_050916.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=September 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920163255/http://www.lgukpublicity.co.uk/uk/images/Prodnotes/BLAIR_WITCH_UK_Production_Notes_FINAL_050916.pdf |archive-date=September 20, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>   \n# \"Pagan Dance Move\"&nbsp;\u2013 [[Arnaud Rebotini]]<ref name=\"what-song.com\"/><ref name=\"lgukpublicity.co.uk\"/>\n# \"Rien \u00e0 Paris\"&nbsp;\u2013 Liz & L\u00e1szl\u00f3<ref name=\"what-song.com\"/><ref name=\"lgukpublicity.co.uk\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of films featuring drones]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.blairwitch.movie/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1540011|Blair Witch}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|blair_witch|Blair Witch}}\n* {{mojo title|woods2016|Blair Witch}}\n* {{Metacritic film|blair-witch|Blair Witch}}\n\n{{Blair Witch}}\n{{Adam Wingard}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blair Witch (film)}}\n[[Category:2010s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2016 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American psychological horror